            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology">East (Mashriq) › Arabia › Gulf</p>
               <p>Sedentary dialect of the Baḥārnah-type</p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <p>The town of al-Qaṭīf is one of the oldest settlements
                  in Eastern Arabia: its
                  history goes back to at least 3500 BC. Before the discovery of oil, the inhabitants of
                  al-Qaṭīf worked as merchants, farmers, and fishermen. The town was the most important
                  trade port on the Arabian shore of the Gulf for centuries.</p>
               <p>The region of al-Qaṭīf is the centre of the Shiite population
                  in Saudi Arabia. The Baḥārnah-type dialect of al-Qatif is very similar to that spoken by the Shiite population in Bahrain.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:4IQWSVPU">Prochazka (1989)</rs> includes a
                  brief grammatical sketch of the dialect spoken by the urban community and oasis of
                  al-Qalʕa, plus information on phonology, morphology, and two interrogative particles.
                  <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:SFCM9CVB">Al-Qaṣṣāb (2004)</rs> contains lexicographical
                  information, a description of the phonology, and a discussion of some pronouns.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="bibliography">
               <p>To view publications on this variety click <rs type="bibl" ref="bibl:geo:Al-Qatif"> here</rs>.</p>
